    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can repot your fiddle leaf fig by first checking if the roots are actually circling tightly inside the root ball rather than just growing straight down, which is a common occurrence. If the roots are indeed circling, repotting into a slightly larger pot with a well-draining soil mix made of peat moss, perlite, and a bit of orchid bark will support its growth. When repotting, gently loosen the root ball, trim any circling or damaged roots, and place the plant in fresh soil without compressing it too tightly to avoid stress. It's also a good idea to water the plant lightly after repotting to help settle the soil around the roots. This process is generally safe if done carefully, and your plant should bounce back quickly.",
